This includes:
- Compliance with industry standards and codes in effect at the time of initial construction and modification;
- Performance of a thorough Process Hazard Analyses (PHAs) at least once every five years using accurate Process Safety Information; 
- Implementation of Operating Procedures which have been reviewed by PHA; 
- Appropriate initial and refresher training of system operations and maintenance personnel;  
- Performance of preventive and corrective maintenance according to system component manufacturer recommendations and pursuant to site wide hazardous energy lockout and hot work permit programs;
- Application of established auditing, inspection, and pre-start-up review protocols; and
- Use of qualified contractors for work on the system.

Five Year Accident History

There have been no ammonia releases within the last 5 years (January 2002 ? January 2007) resulting in onsite or off-site injuries, deaths, or property damage, or in off-site environmental damage, evacuations, or sheltering in place. 

Emergency Response Program

Sara Lee has developed an Emergency Planning and Response document to ensure adequate preparedness with rapid and appropriate response to ammonia release emergencies. The plan is maintained at the site?s Safety Office. The document describes outside agency notification procedures in the event of an ammonia release, provides detailed evacuation procedures, and includes response procedures for the mitigation of ammonia releases. 

The Fire Department will be used to respond to any catastrophic leaks. The plant has a trained "Emergency Rescue Team" for non-confined space personnel rescues and escape. In the event of a catastrophic leak, Sara Lee will evacuate and take initial life safety precautions.

